EIS 21
[normal]Written evidence submitted by David Highley[bold]Executive Summary:[bold]Adequate supplies of miner
[normal]als are essential for economic 
[normal]development. 
[normal]For its small size Britain is 
[normal]relatively
[normal] well endowed with mineral resources and their e
[normal]xtraction and use have played an important part in the historic development of the UK economy. The UK continues to have an economically 
[normal]significant
[normal] minerals industry, with oil and gas, and construction and in
[normal]dustrial minerals being important sectors. Although much diminished, coal still makes an important contribution to our energy mix. The contribution that these minerals make 
[normal]to
[normal] the national economy 
[normal]may
[normal] be considered 
[normal]in two
[normal] ways. First there is the primary c
[normal]ontribution they make in terms of added value and employment associated with 
[normal]their
[normal] extraction and processing; and then there is the secondary 
[normal]contribution they
[normal] make to the competitiveness of the
[normal] downstream
[normal] industries they support. Nevertheless, the UK 
[normal]also 
[normal]has 
[normal]substantial
[normal] and increasing 
[normal]foreign
[normal] dependence for minera
[normal]l supplies. This not only places
[normal] 
[normal]increasing 
[normal]demands
[normal] on the environments of ou
[normal]r trading partners
[normal] but potentially makes us more vulnerable to supply disruptions 
[normal]as global demand for minerals gr
[normal]owths driven by expanding populations and rising incomes. There will be a continuing demand for the products of the UK’s extractive industries for the foreseeable future.
[normal] 
[normal]This submission principally responds to the following question in the BIS Committee
[normal]’s 
[normal]Call for Evidence[bold] on 2
[normal]nd
[normal] July 2013:
