[normal]Since 1970 UK mineral production has been dominated by
[normal] energy minerals, initially coal, but later oil and gas following the development of 
[normal]large 
[normal]of
[normal]fshore reserves from the 1970s. The 
[normal]value of coal production 
[normal]has declined in line with 
[normal]steadily 
[normal]falling output since the mid-1980
[normal]s
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]rapidly 
[normal]rising value of oil production up to 1984 was reversed by t
[normal]he slump in world 
[normal]oil 
[normal]prices at the end of 1985, and
[normal] again in 1988, and also the loss of production through the Piper Alpha tragedy
[normal].
[normal] Following rising oil prices since 2000, however, the value of UK oil productions has risen and was still £25.5 billion in 2011
[normal].
[normal] Despite falling oil and gas production since 2000, the value of both have held up well because of high prices.  Ultimately, however, as reserves are depleted their value will decline.
[normal]11.
[normal]    
[normal]The value of construction and industrial minerals has also falle
[normal]n, reflecting the decline in the production of 
[normal]some 
[normal]industrial minerals such as kaolin, b
[normal]ut mainly because of the recently
[normal] significantly depressed state of the UK construction industry and its impact on aggregates production in particular. Although too sma
[normal]ll to show on Figure 1, the decline in the value of metalliferous minerals production is principally because of the demise of tin mining in Cornwall in the 1990s. 
[normal]1
[normal]2
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he value to the UK economy of minerals produced from indigenous sources is, however, de
[normal]rived not only from the minerals themselves but also the downstream 
[normal]industries and employment these support. Low cost construction and industrial minerals, in particular, serve as essential raw materials for the construction, cement, 
[normal]asphalt, 
[normal]concrete prod
[normal]ucts, 
[normal]inorganic chemicals, glass, ceramics, lime,
[normal] plaster products, 
[normal]and castings
[normal] industries were the value added may be several fold.   The economic benefits derived from the domestic extractive industries goes much further than the values indicated sugges
[normal]t
[normal].
