[normal]              
[normal]An overview of the contribution that the extractive industries make to the UK economy can be found in a report produced by the British Geological 
[normal]Survey in 2004
[normal]. 
[normal]Although t
[normal]he statistics are now somewhat dated, the principles that are presented 
[normal]in the report 
[normal]have not changed significantly, 
[normal]with the exception 
[normal]that 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK has
[normal] become even more dependent on 
[normal]imports of minerals and mineral
[normal]–based products
[normal]. This report, together with a wealth of other information on the UK minerals industry, can be found on the British Geological Survey’s dedicated minerals website – 
[normal]www.mineralsUK.com
[normal] .  In particular I would refer
[normal] you to the series of 
[normal]Mineral Planning Factsheets
[normal], which provide succinct overviews of 
[normal]each of the 
[normal]economically important minerals extracted onshore in Britain, and also to the 
[normal]United Kingdom Minerals Yearbook
[normal] referred to above. 
[normal]14.
[normal]              
[normal]Conclusions[bold]. [bold]Adequate 
[normal]supplies of minerals are ess
[normal]ential for economic development. Whilst there has been a decoupling of economic growth with minerals consumption 
[normal]in recent years 
[normal]this may indicate that the economy is under investing
[normal] 
[normal]in infrastructure and housing and also forego
[normal]ing the value  added  by working and processing domestic (and imported) minerals in favour of importing higher value manufactured products containing embedded minerals. Moves to try and rebalance the economy and increased investment in 
[normal]housing and 
[normal]infrastr
[normal]ucture as economic growth improves and 
[normal]the population expands could reverse the declining trend in minerals consumption. 
[normal]Britain’s resource security and its longer term access to mineral supplies, both from domestic and overseas sources, will remain a key 
[normal]issue for the national economy for many years to come.
[normal] There will be a continuing demand for the products of the UK’s extractive industries for the foreseeable future and we should
[normal] make the best use of
[normal] our domestic mineral resources (and waste streams), where economically and environmentally feasible to do so.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Mineral
[normal] Products Association estimate
[normal]s
[normal] that the annual turnover of th
[normal]eir industry is about £9 billion and supports over £400 billion turnover in the industries they supply. 
